english:
  title: Epitaph for Lord Yun of Pabyeong with Preface
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the winter of Zhizhen's xinchounian, when bandits pressed upon the capital, the Xuanling decided to journey south. Many officials abandoned their posts and fled. Lord Yun Hae of Pabyeong, formerly Governor of Fuzhou, followed the royal carriage on horseback. At Guangzhou, he sat at the guest house door, conversing and laughing as if on an ordinary day. Thus I first came to know his face—truly, a remarkable man. When I lay ill, he came to inquire after me. Seeing his expression, he seemed deeply moved by my suffering. I have never forgotten this kindness. Alas, five years have passed since the Lord's death, and now, while still weak from illness, I inscribe these humble words upon his tomb. Is this not cause for reflection?

    The Lord's given name was Hae, his courtesy name Ziqi, a man of Pabyeong County. His thirteenth-generation ancestor Sinda was called a Meritorious Subject of the Three Han. He begat Gongsinxianzhi, who begat Gongsin Jingang, Left Servant of the Horse. Jingang begat Right Servant Zhiheng. Zhiheng begat the Duke Guan, whose titles included Grand Guardian of the State, who cut down the Jurchen invaders in the time of the Wise King and set up a stone to commemorate the deed. Guan begat Yanyi, Prime Minister of the Central Secretariat, a man of great resolve who understood the nature of life and death, and who composed a poem upon his deathbed that read like the utterances of Buddhist masters. Yanyi begat Dunxin, Palace Attendant of the Ministry of War. Dunxin begat Shangji, Minor Commandant of the Guard. Shangji begat Fuyuan, Recorder of the Court of Imperial Sacrifices, the Lord's great-grandfather. Fuyuan begat the Lord's grandfather, Inspector Chun. Chun begat the Lord's father, Keeper of the Privy Purse, who took to wife the daughter of Park Zhiliang, Commander of a Thousand and High Official of the Three Departments. The Lord was born in the seventh month of Yuanzheng's dingweiyear.

    At fourteen, through family privilege he entered service as Warden of Zhouling. In Zhiyuan's gengcheneyear, he was promoted to Distinguished Protector of the Xingwei Guard, rising to the rank of Eminent Counselor and receiving the purple-gold fish-emblem. The following year he became Keeper of Rites and Vice Director of the Bureau of Ceremonial, conducting all processions with perfect propriety. Among forty-some protectors, all brave and bold men who scorned restraint, the Lord alone adhered to ritual, and his manner became the model for generations.

    In the renuwu year, he rose to Guard of the Inner Retinue. At this time, the examining official Min Saiping's servant went outside the walls to gather wood and cut living pine. When the Duty Master Yin'an, passing through the suburbs, saw this and properly forbade it, the servants, not knowing he was the Duty Master, struck him and wounded his leg. The King grew wrathful and ordered the residence of the examining official destroyed. But the Lord spoke thus: "The servant is indeed guilty, but what does his master have to do with this? Moreover, now when many scholars anxiously await the posting of the examination results, how can the examining official conduct his duties with an undisturbed mind if his house is demolished?" Shortly after, the King's anger subsided and the matter was shelved.

    In the guiyeyear, he rose to Senior Guardian of the Three Departments. In three years as official of the Treasuring-Prosperity Storehouse, he proved so honest that when another great official audited the accounts, only the Lord was found blameless, earning high praise. When officials of the Censorate were selected, all the great ministers said: "Lord Yun comes from a line that has for generations upheld propriety and maintained integrity. None equals him in understanding the essentials of administration." Thus he became Executive Censor, where he presented many memorials, though not all were implemented. Yet his name resounded through the realm. His colleague Censor Zheng Guojing, likewise renowned for his purity and courage, earned the people's respect. The Censorate was said to hold "the great principles in the grasp of the Executive Censor, the symbols of authority in the hands of the Assistant." The scholar-officials held them in admiration.

    In the gengyinyear, he became Prefect of Judicial Affairs. His judgments were fair and just, and the people harbored no resentment. In the wuyear of Xuanling's reign, he was appointed Upper Protector of the Gate Guard. The officials of the Central Authority, knowing his reputation and fearing his probity, dared not deceive him. After a month came his appointment as Governor of Fuzhou, where he governed with such wisdom that the people prospered.

    In the winter of xinchounian, he commanded his son, now Privy Councilor: "I cannot but go to where the King is. You and your mother must follow by the shorter route." Thus he accompanied the King as Commander of Conscript Forces for Gyeongsang Province. When the capital was restored and merit was recorded, his rank was second class. Those who knew his worth urged him to protest this injustice, but he merely smiled and said nothing.

    In jiachenyear, he rose to Prefect of Ceremonial Affairs. In renzioyear, he became Minister of Judicial Affairs. In jiayinyear's winter, he was enfeoffed as Lord of Pabyeong and raised to the rank of Grand Magnifico. The Lord once remarked: "Our family has produced scholars in seven consecutive generations since my ancestor the Minister of the Palace, yet what good does it do us now to regret?" On the twelfth day of the twelfth month of bingchenyear, he passed from illness in his residence at age seventy. The following year, on jiagriday of the first month, he was buried at the ancestral tomb of Songrim.

    His wife was of the Cui family, daughter of the Court Official and Censor-General Yong. She bore four sons and two daughters. The eldest son, Ho, became Prefect of the Privy Council and Upper Protector. The other sons died young. The eldest daughter married Prefect of the Interior Kim Hoejok; the second married Governor Liu Wonmu of Yeohung. There are numerous grandchildren. The Privy Councilor took to wife the daughter of Governor Yi Wonhu of Seon and begat one son and two daughters. His calligraphy was excellent, his skill at go remarkable. The Xuanling came to know and favor him, commanding him to inscribe an ancient poem. When he wrote verses of moonlit dewdrops and wind-scattered flowers, the Lord declined: "Such things are unfit for the throne." Instead he wrote:

    In darkness one may deceive, yet not always;
    To deceive in light brings death and shame.
    With but one man's hand,
    Can one cover all the eyes of heaven and earth?

    When the King read these words, he said: "This is subtle remonstrance!" and thereafter kept the Counselor at a distance. Yet the worthy said: "The Lord did not betray his learning." Truly, Lord Pabyeong had a worthy son.

    The Counselor also said: "My father was not fond of wine in his daily life, yet when he drank he knew no limit. He lived without illness. By nature he favored simplicity, rarely ate meat, in summer always wore complete dress, in winter never doubled his robes. He kept far from music and beauty. He studied deeply the statutes and administrative codes. That Heaven did not grant him longer days—alas, alas, what could be done?"

    Thus I know the Lord had a virtuous son indeed.

    The epitaph reads:

    The fief of Yongpyeong
    the King bestowed on Lord Yun.
    Armed forces dispatched, lands opened,
    His merit raised upon the stone.
    The founder of the office he inherited
    was the Lord's grandfather—
    the Lord carried on the line,
    filling positions of honor.

    The Lord's name—
    only his righteousness shone clear.
    Yet station matched not virtue;
    who can measure such fairness?
    This grave inscription
    will endure for ages hence.
    No flattery is mine—
    the Lord had a worthy son.
